Split into Train & Test data¶

In [24]:
# Import `train_test_split` from `sklearn.model_selection`
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split

# Specify the data 
X=df.iloc[:,np.r_[0:8,9:14]]

# Specify the target labels and flatten array
y= df.Exited

# Split the data up in train and test sets
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, test_size=0.30, random_state=42)

Scaling the Train & Test data¶

In [25]:
from sklearn.preprocessing import MinMaxScaler

cols_to_scale = ['CreditScore','Age','Tenure','Balance','EstimatedSalary','NumOfProducts']
# Define the scaler 
scaler = MinMaxScaler()

# Scale the train set
X_train[cols_to_scale] = scaler.fit_transform(X_train[cols_to_scale].to_numpy())

# Scale the test set
X_test[cols_to_scale] = scaler.transform(X_test[cols_to_scale].to_numpy())

Building the Model¶

In [28]:
import tensorflow as tf
from tensorflow.keras.layers import Dense,Flatten
from tensorflow.keras.models import Sequential, Model
model=Sequential()
model.add(Flatten(input_shape=(13,)))
model.add(Dense(100,activation='relu'))
model.add(Dense(1,activation='sigmoid'))
In [29]:
model.compile(optimizer='adam',metrics=['accuracy'],loss='BinaryCrossentropy')
In [30]:
model.fit(X_train,y_train,batch_size=64,validation_split=0.1,epochs=100)
